(6)

where Ri is the van der Waals radius of i (1/2 of the distance to the energy minimum in the Lennard-Jones potential),␭i is a correlation length, and ␣i is a proportionality coefficient given by

␣i ϭ 2⌬Gifree/ͱ␲␭i

(7)

where ⌬Gfiree is the solvation free energy of the free (isolated) group i; ⌬Gfiree is close to ⌬Grief but not identical to it and is determined empirically by requiring that the solvation free energy of deeply buried groups be zero (see below). The parameters used in the model are given in Table I.
Given Equations 3–6, the solvation free energy evaluation requires a choice of atom types i, their volumes Vi, their correlation length ␭i , ⌬Grief, and ⌬Gfiree. The speciﬁc atom types and solvation parameters are chosen to be used in conjunction with the CHARMM 19 polar hydrogen energy function. The atom types (Table I) are those used in CHARMM 19. To simplify the treatment of electrostatic interactions (see below), the ionic side-chains are neutralized and a linear distance-dependent dielectric constant is used (⑀ ϭ r). Also, certain choices were made for calculating the nonbonded interactions. Both van der Waals and electrostatic interactions are cut off at 9 A˚ with a switching function used between 7 and 9A˚ . Electrostatic interactions are calculated on a group-by-group basis. The value of ␭i was taken to be the thickness of one hydration shell (3.5 A˚ ) except for the neutralized ionic groups, for which a value of 6 A˚ was used.

Other Thermodynamic Quantities
The same model can be used to calculate other solvation properties, such as the solvation enthalpy, entropy, and heat capacity with the appropriate reference solvation values for the enthalpy and heat capacity. These values make it possible to calculate the solvation free energies at any temperature T. Assuming that the heat capacity is independent of temperature, we have

