(18)

It is important to note that ⌬Gifree is not exactly equal to ⌬Giref, the solvation free energy of i in the model compound. This is true because other groups are bonded to group i in
the model compound and exclude solvent from its vicinity. For this reason, we expect ⌬Gifree, which corresponds to the isolated atom in solution, to be larger in magnitude than ⌬Giref. In the present model, we determined ⌬Gifree by requiring that the solvation free energy of groups deeply
buried inside a protein be approximately zero. For each group, the magnitude of ⌬Gifree was incremented (starting from ⌬Giref) until the solvation free energy of some groups of that type in the protein CI2 became approximately zero
(it is not possible to make all fully buried groups have
exactly zero solvation free energy because even fully
buried groups differ somewhat in the number of atoms surrounding them). This procedure led to the ⌬Gifree values listed in Table I. They are all larger in magnitude than

